body:
### Bug explanation

I have the following code to switch between dark and light themes.  Since updating to 5.0 this no longer works.  Theme.Dark and Theme.Light dont exist any more.  Also swatch.AccentExemplarHue is gone.  I cant remember where I got this code from but it was working.  The Advanced theming page in the wiki will also be incorrect now.

```
var sp = new SwatchesProvider();
var swatch = sp.Swatches.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Name == "deeppurple");
if (swatch != null)
{
  var darkTheme = Theme.Create(Theme.Dark, swatch.ExemplarHue.Color, swatch.AccentExemplarHue.Color);
  var lightTheme = Theme.Create(Theme.Light, swatch.ExemplarHue.Color, swatch.AccentExemplarHue.Color);
  new PaletteHelper().SetTheme(_darkTheme ? darkTheme : lightTheme);
}
```

### Version

5.0

comments.body:
I don't know if it's the "right way", but try this

```
var newTheme = _darkTheme ? BaseTheme.Dark : BaseTheme.Light;
var colorKey = nameof(MaterialDesignColor.DeepPurple);
var swatchProvider = new SwatchesProvider();
var swatch = swatchProvider.Swatches.FirstOrDefault(x => string.Equals(x.Name, colorKey, StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));
if (swatch != null)
{
    var paletteHelper = new PaletteHelper();
    var theme = paletteHelper.GetTheme();
    theme.SetBaseTheme(newTheme);
    theme.SetPrimaryColor(swatch.ExemplarHue.Color);
    theme.SetSecondaryColor(swatch.SecondaryExemplarHue?.Color ?? swatch.ExemplarHue.Color); //nullable SecondaryExemplarHue? I don't know what to do here.
    paletteHelper.SetTheme(theme);
}
```

Thanks people :)

This works:
```
var ph = new PaletteHelper();
var theme = ph.GetTheme();
if (theme != null)
{
  if (_darkTheme)
    theme.SetDarkTheme();
  else
    theme.SetLightTheme();
  ph.SetTheme(theme);
}
```

I assume the popup is likely what is causing the issue if the HikVision SDK is expected to be able to get ahold of window handle. Popups are their own lightweight window and separate from the main window. 
There are a couple things I would suggest trying. 

1. Switch to using the embedded dialog host (`Style="{StaticResource MaterialDesignEmbeddedDialogHost}"`). This secondary style embeds the dialog directly inside of the window's visual tree rather than using a popup. The disadvantage here is that the dialog's size cannot exceed the containing window (while the popup allows that). If that restriction is acceptable, that is likely the simples option.

2. Manually parse the visual tree to get the popup control. Depending on how you are setting up the dialog something like this as the DialogOpened event handler can get your the handle for the PopupEx.
```C#
private void DialogHost_DialogOpened(object sender, DialogOpenedEventArgs eventArgs)
{
    IntPtr handle = IntPtr.Zero;
    for (var @do = (DependencyObject)eventArgs.Session.Content;
        @do != null;
        @do = VisualTreeHelper.GetParent(@do) ?? LogicalTreeHelper.GetParent(@do))
    {
        if (@do is Visual visual &&
            PresentationSource.FromVisual(visual) is HwndSource source)
        {
            handle = source.Handle;
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

